NEWS: Our correspondents worldwide report
---------------------------------------------------------------------------

MALAYSIA: No distinctions in university rankings

Geoff Maslen
A rating of 47 Malaysian universities and other higher education
institutions, including seven set up by foreign universities, has classed
18 as =91excellent=92, 25 as =91very good=92 and four as =91good=92. None e=
arned a
=91distinction=92. Releasing the ratings last week, Higher Education Minist=
er
Datuk Seri Mohamed Khaled Nordin said the
http://www.mqa.gov.my/SETARA09/index.cfm would be used by the Higher
Education Ministry in developing =93appropriate higher education policies=
=94.
Full report on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100716193343889

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

MYANMAR: Remembering the 1988 student generation

David Jardine
As another anniversary of the violent repression of Burma=92s (now
Myanmar=92s) democratic uprising of 1988 approaches, a new book Than Shwe:
Unmasking Burma=92s tyrant* recalls the sacrifices made then by the country=
=92s
university students, the 8.8.88 generation.
Full report on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100716193214207

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

RUSSIA: Promoting higher education abroad

Eugene Vorotnikov
Faced with a declining share of the global education export market, the
Russian government plans to raise the prestige of local universities by
attracting foreign students and creating opportunities for their employment
within the country.
Full report on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100716193054921

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

US: Responding to the =91brain drain=92 reversal

Sarah King Head
How can the purportedly slowing rate of H-1B visa applications from
postgraduates to the US State Department since April 2010 be interpreted? A
recent article in
http://money.cnn.com/2010/06/14/news/economy/immigration_brain_drain.fortun=
e/index.htm
magazine suggests the reversal of the so-called =93brain drain=94 points to=
 a
worrying trend related to perceived long-term consequences of the current
economic recession and the waning appeal of the spec ialised job market in
the US.
Full report on the University World News site :
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20100717193828207
